habitat_description: This species is found from Mendocino County, California, north to extreme southwest British Columbia, Canada. Its distribution is restricted to the Coast and Cascade Ranges, and the Olympic Peninsula (Nussbaum 1976; McAllister 1995). The range extends from approximately Anchor Bay in California north of the Chilliwack River basin in the extreme southwestern region of British Columbia through the Coast and Cascades Ranges, but not in the Olympic Peninsula (Green et al. 2013). Breeding habitat consists of pools and slow moving areas of streams (Nussbaum 1969). This species (named Pacific giant salamander) has an elevational range from near sea level up to 2160 meters (Stebbins 2003). This species is found in successional forests, but within-stream conditions resulted in better presence predictors (Welsh 1993). Paedomorphic individuals are associated with permanent water bodies (Nussbaum et al. 1983).
